item.title: Lifecam VX-3000 Support for Ender 3
item.description:
This is a mount for the Microsoft LifeCam VX-3000 to attach to Ender-3.

Remix of the C270 Webcam support for Ender 3- remodel of the mount only. All other pieces created by OP Waverunner62. Cheers from Canada friend, my name is also Eric!

Used the old mount as a base to expand model to support the shape and size of the webcam I already owned, the Microsoft LifeCam VX-3000.

Printed on Ender-3 Max in about 12 hours in total. There is a clip base and a screw base to screw onto existing printer hardware. I recommend using the 45° angle screw base for stability. Print at least 3 arms for full length and maneuverability. Use supports for the camera mount piece and print vertically aligned for best results. The rest of the pieces are best printed horizontally. Zip-ties for webcam cord is not necessary but can be used if you prefer.

Hardware:
4x M4 30mm bolts
4x M4 Nuts
item.author: lunarLarceny

item.title: lightbearer laser engraver
item.description:
this is a custom core-xy frame for laser engraving. This is, in my honest opinion, the most user friendly frame. Super easy to assemble and minimum adjustment requires on belt tension to get it to work perfectly square. using mgn12 linear rails, there is minimum to no play on the axes. i have done my best, also, to keep the weight of the laser head the most centered and close to the x aluminium profile. Belt path is optimized and aligned with the frame.

BOM:

2040x600 (x2)
2020x600 (x3)
mgn12h x500mm (x3), optional: you can go for 550mm for the x but those are are to find
gt2 belt 6mm wide x 5m (2x2,5m)
gt2 toothed idlers 3mm i.d. (x6)
gt2 toothless idlers 5mm i.d (x2) because i didnt have 3mm i.d. toothless on hand but will update a newer version soon with 3mm i.d. ones.
gt2 16 teeth sprocket (for steppers)
0.9 nema17 steppers
2209/2208 stepper driver
your choice of board (im using arduino with a cnc shield)
15x10 cable drag chain
12v (5amp minimum) power supply
atomstack a5 laser head used for this project, if you need a different laserhead holder just let me know, in the meanwhile i will upload some more optional holder for the other brand so you could use your choice of laserhead.

item.title: Engagement Ring Case with Lithophane Insert (Screws Required)
item.description:
Full model can be purchased and downloaded from my Cults3D page:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/jewelry/engagement-ring-case-with-lithophane-insert-screws-required

Made this beautiful engagement ring case for my fiancee last christmas, just in time for Christmas Eve proposal. Now, you can too!

Case dimensions 36mm (H) x 55mm (L) x 55mm (W) when closed.

Lid hinge is designed such that the lid can stay up-right to the casing body without generating too much friction. Click-snap feature along the tip edge of the lid. Sand it down as required, but I found mine one printed okay.

You can mount a lithophane portrait with dimensions of 35mm x 35mm x 3mm thick, at the back of the lid, then supported by the 2 layers of Lithophane support inserts and 3x M3 counter sunk screws.

I use this free lithophane maker here:
(https://lithophanemaker.com/Framed%20Lithophane.html)

The ring cushion will be a separate insert to the casing body. Best to be printed with TPU filament as it is elastic.

DISCLAIMER: Avoid printing the ring cushion with hard material, otherwise it can potentially scratch your ring.

Recommended ring dimensions for the current ring cushion design:

Width of the band all the way around = 2.2mm
Depth of band = 1.5mm
Outside diameter = 19.5mm
Height from top of diamond to outside base of shank = 24mm

Following screws will be required to complete the assembly:
2 x Pan Head Screws M2.5 x 16mm long - for fixing the hinge.
3 x Counter Sunk Screws M3 x 6mm long - for fixing the lithophane on lid.

My case body and lid was printed using CCTREE Copper Filled PLA filament for elegant effect.
(https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B074W1WQL8/)

Apply few coats of Hycote spray for the fine polishing finish:
(https://www.amazon.co.uk/Hycote-Clear-Lacquer-400ml-Energy/dp/B004SNLNY2)

item.title: Pathtag Sherpa
item.description:
I designed this sherpa to be the diameter of a geocoin. The hole is large enough to hold a standard pathtag, and there's a small hole under it to glue in a 6x2mm magnet. I've included three STL files:

1) Full.stl is 5mm thick and can be used to hold a pathtag on one side and a sticker on the other.

2) Cutout.stl is 4.1mm thick and contains both holes. The intention is to attach it to another thin part (44.1mm in diameter) to create your own pathtag holder. Glue a "Coin" to a "Cutout" along with a magnet.

3) Coin.stl is a sample design with something like the Pathtags logo. If you print the first layers in yellow, then swap to blue for the middle, and finally white for the last, it'll match the picture. I use .15mm resolution with the first layer at .3mm, so for me this was only 8 layers, and the first 2 layers were yellow (the star), the next 3 layers were blue, and the Iast 3 layers were white (the dots). Maybe you could design something personal for your own use.

You might want to add a little "bump" around the magnet's hole to allow the pathtag to come out more easily. The way it is now, the fit is not tight, but the magnet holds it pretty securely, and it takes a "thwack" against your hand to get the pathtag out. A bump in the middle would allow you to just press down on one side of the pathtag to get the other side to pop up for easy removal. I like it a little more secure.

item.title: Truck Tonneau Cover Lever
item.description:
This is a replacement lever for the tonneau cover on my Ford Ranger. I couldn't find any designs that matched the one I already had (and I didn't want to spend the $30-40 on a new one) so I designed my own.

The original is made out of a more flexible plastic that allows for tension between the top and bottom pieces. Since I printed this in PLA, I had to come up with another way to lock the lever in place, which I did with a small notch on the top piece. Because of this, the lever sort of snaps a bit when unlocking (when I tested it on my truck) but it should smooth out a bit over time.

I also included an unthreaded barrel nut that I used (just forced the bolt through to create a thread and it holds well). Metal would be nicer but I wasn't able to find an M6 barrel nut anywhere in my city.

It's not perfect but it seems to work enough. Any remixes to improve it would be great!

I've uploaded a picture of it in use, along with the original one on the other side of the truck (in black) to compare.
item.author: GooseShaw

item.title: Traxxas Maxx wheelie bar wheels with tires
item.description: The Traxxas Maxx factory wheelie bar wheels make an awful scratching sound whenever they come into contact with cement. These wheels for the wheelie bar are designed to employ a TPU tire so it's nice and quiet. The wheel can be printed in PLA, PETG, ABS, whatever really. The factory axle and spacer parts inside the original wheels are used in these replacement wheels as well. Traxxas part number 5119a is a bearing that can be used to replace the factory plastic spacers if one wishes but is not necessary.

item.title: Qidi i-fast Front Gap Cover/Vent
item.description:
This was created to fill the front gap in the Qidi i-fast. It simply clips in along the inner edge of the door frame. Two sided tape can be used to secure the bottom and to secure the two pieces together. Each vent will cover half of the gap so you will need to print two.

I will eventually remix this to flare out a bit at the bottom edge to follow the contour of the printer a bit more tightly along the edges but these work well and leave very little space once installed.

I printed them using a tough PLA. Time will tell if they warp once I crank the heat up in the chamber but at 80 degrees celsius they had no issues.
